721709f-a.text:
Morningside (left) and Manhattan (right) Avenues, at W. 114 th Street, showing the Washington and Lafayette Statue. Placque on same reads "Lafayette-Washington, presented to the City of New York by Chas. S. Rouss, April 19, 1900". Incidentally the donor, a merchant, was popularly known as "Broadway Rouss". Belonging to the late 90's he started as a peddler and thru thrift and enterprise he developed a huge organization with headquarters on Broadway.
1920
Copyright, American Studio
Gift of Urbrock Collection

721710f-b.text:
Morningside (left) and Manhattan (right) Avenue's, north from West 114th Street, and showing the small triangular park at this point. Standing in the latter is the Lafayette Monument. Morningside Park is at the extreme left
tho it does not appear.
No. 1: November, 1904
1906
